      →…
   145→### Why?
   146→
   147→There are lots of existing validation libraries—[`joi`](https://github.com/hapijs/joi), [`express-validator`](https://github.com/ctavan/express-validator), [`validator.js`](https://github.com/chriso/validator.js), [`yup`](https://github.com/jquense/yup), [`ajv`](https://github.com/epoberezkin/ajv), [`is-my-json-valid`](https://github.com/mafintosh/is-my-json-valid)... But they exhibit many issues that lead to your codebase becoming hard to maintain...
   148→
   149→- **They don't expose detailed errors.** Many validators simply return string-only errors or booleans without any details as to why, making it difficult to customize the errors to be helpful for end-users.
   150→
   151→- **They make custom types hard.** Many validators ship with built-in types like emails, URLs, UUIDs, etc. with no way to know what they check for, and complicated APIs for defining new types.
   152→
      →…
   167→### Principles
   168→
   169→1. **Customizable types.** Superstruct's power is in making it easy to define an entire set of custom data types that are specific to your application, and defined in a _single_ place, so you have full control over your requirements.
   170→
   171→2. **Unopinionated defaults.** Superstruct ships with native JavaScript types, and everything else is customizable, so you never have to fight to override decisions made by "core" that differ from your application's needs.
   172→
   173→3. **Composable interfaces.** Superstruct interfaces are composable, so you can break down commonly-repeated pieces of data into components, and compose them to build up the more complex objects.
   174→
      →…
   181→### Demo
   182→
   183→Try out the [live demo on CodeSandbox](https://codesandbox.io/s/bold-water-s2cr8d?file=/index.js) to get an idea for how the API works, or to quickly verify your use case:
   184→
   185→[![Demo screenshot.](./docs/images/demo-screenshot.png)](https://codesandbox.io/s/bold-water-s2cr8d?file=/index.js)
   186→
   187→<br/>
   188→
   189→### Examples
   190→
   191→Superstruct's API is very flexible, allowing it to be used for a variety of use cases on your servers and in the browser. Here are a few examples of common patterns...
   192→
   193→- [Basic Validation](./examples/basic-validation.js)
   194→- [Custom Types](./examples/custom-types.js)
   195→- [Default Values](./examples/default-values.js)
   196→- [Optional Values](./examples/optional-values.js)
      →…
   205→### Documentation
   206→
   207→Read the getting started guide to familiarize yourself with how Superstruct works. After that, check out the full API reference for more detailed information about structs, types and errors...
   208→
   209→- [**Guide**](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/01-getting-started)
   210→  - [Getting Started](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/01-getting-started)
   211→  - [Validating Data](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/02-validating-data)
   212→  - [Coercing Data](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/03-coercing-data)
