docs/readme.md
     7→### Usage
     8→
     9→Superstruct allows you to define the shape of data you want to validate:
    10→
    11→```js
    12→import { assert, object, number, string, array } from 'superstruct'
    13→
    14→const Article = object({
    15→  id: number(),
    16→  title: string(),
    17→  tags: array(string()),
    18→  author: object({
    19→    id: number(),
    20→  }),
    21→})
    22→
    23→const data = {
    24→  id: 34,
    25→  title: 'Hello World',
    26→  tags: ['news', 'features'],
    27→  author: {
    28→    id: 1,
    29→  },
    30→}
    31→
    32→assert(data, Article)
    33→// This will throw an error when the data is invalid.
    34→// If you'd rather not throw, you can use `is()` or `validate()`.
    35→```
    36→
    37→Superstruct ships with validators for all the common JavaScript data types, and you can define custom ones too:
    38→
    39→```js
    40→import { is, define, object, string } from 'superstruct'
    41→import isUuid from 'is-uuid'
    42→import isEmail from 'is-email'
    43→
    44→const Email = define('Email', isEmail)
    45→const Uuid = define('Uuid', isUuid.v4)
    46→
    47→const User = object({
    48→  id: Uuid,
    49→  email: Email,
    50→  name: string(),
    51→})
    52→
    53→const data = {
    54→  id: 'c8d63140-a1f7-45e0-bfc6-df72973fea86',
    55→  email: 'jane@example.com',
    56→  name: 'Jane',
    57→}
    58→
    59→if (is(data, User)) {
    60→  // Your data is guaranteed to be valid in this block.
    61→}
    62→```
    63→
    64→Superstruct can also handle coercion of your data before validating it, for example to mix in default values:
    65→
    66→```ts
    67→import { create, object, number, string, defaulted } from 'superstruct'
    68→
    69→const User = object({
    70→  id: defaulted(number(), () => 1),
    71→  name: string(),
    72→})
    73→
    74→const data = {
    75→  name: 'Jane',
    76→}
    77→
    78→// You can apply the defaults to your data while validating.
    79→const user = create(data, User)
    80→// {
    81→//   id: 1,
    82→//   name: 'Jane',
    83→// }
    84→```
    85→
    86→And if you use TypeScript, Superstruct automatically ensures that your data has proper typings whenever you validate it:
    87→
    88→```ts
    89→import { is, object, number, string } from 'superstruct'
    90→
    91→const User = object({
    92→  id: number(),
    93→  name: string()
    94→})
    95→
    96→const data: unknown = { ... }
    97→
    98→if (is(data, User)) {
      →…
